# Problems

There are a few problems with this setup.

## Interface as Element Type

You are telling the `FXMLLoader` to instantiate a [`List`][3] _directly_. This is not possible, because that type is an interface and interfaces cannot be instantiated. You would have to use a concrete implementation, such as [`ArrayList`][4].

This problem is where your current error is coming from:

&gt; ```none
&gt; Caused by: java.lang.InstantiationException: java.util.List
&gt;         at java.lang.Class.newInstance(Unknown Source)
&gt;         at sun.reflect.misc.ReflectUtil.newInstance(Unknown Source)
&gt;         at javafx.fxml.FXMLLoader$InstanceDeclarationElement.constructValue(FXMLLoader.java:1009)
&gt;         ... 15 more
&gt; Caused by: java.lang.NoSuchMethodException: java.util.List.&lt;init&gt;()
&gt;         at java.lang.Class.getConstructor0(Unknown Source)
&gt; ```

## Incorrect Reference

You are referencing the list incorrectly. Because the list is from the controller, it should look like:

```xml
&lt;fx:reference source=&quot;controller.list&quot;/&gt;
```

But it will still complain about that value not existing. The `FXMLLoader` does not do field access when trying to _get_ a value. It looks for an appropriate getter method instead. For instance, here we&#39;re telling the loader to get the `list` property of the controller instance, and so it looks for a `getList()` method in the controller class. So, that method needs to exist.


```java
public List&lt;Label&gt; getList() {
    return list;
}
```

## Adding List to &quot;Read-Only List Property&quot;

_**Warning:** This problem would seem to make your approach impractical, if not impossible._

You are trying to populate the `children` list of the `VBox`. That list is known as a [&quot;read-only list property&quot;][1]. Unfortunately, the linked documentation says nothing about being able to add a _collection_ to such properties (e.g., via `addAll`):

&gt; A read-only list property is a Bean property whose getter returns an instance of `java.util.List` and has no corresponding setter method. The contents of a read-only list element are automatically added to the list as they are processed.
&gt;
&gt;For example, the &quot;children&quot; property of `javafx.scene.Group` is a read-only list property representing the group&#39;s child nodes:
&gt;
&gt; ```xml
&gt; &lt;?import javafx.scene.*?&gt;
&gt; &lt;?import javafx.scene.shape.*?&gt;
&gt; &lt;Group xmlns:fx=&quot;http://javafx.com/fxml&quot;&gt;
&gt;     &lt;children&gt;
&gt;         &lt;Rectangle fx:id=&quot;rectangle&quot; x=&quot;10&quot; y=&quot;10&quot; width=&quot;320&quot; height=&quot;240&quot;
&gt;             fill=&quot;#ff0000&quot;/&gt;
&gt;         ...
&gt;     &lt;/children&gt;
&gt; &lt;/Group&gt;
&gt; ```
&gt;
&gt; As each sub-element of the `&lt;children&gt;` element is read, it is added to the list returned by `Group#getChildren()`.

And trying it out, you get an error like the following:

```none
Caused by: java.lang.IllegalArgumentException: Unable to coerce [[Label@15af0be5[styleClass=label]&#39;Foo&#39;, Label@49a4edc6[styleClass=label]&#39;Bar&#39;]] to class javafx.scene.Node.
        at javafx.fxml/com.sun.javafx.fxml.BeanAdapter.coerce(BeanAdapter.java:497)
        at javafx.fxml/javafx.fxml.FXMLLoader$Element.add(FXMLLoader.java:174)
        at javafx.fxml/javafx.fxml.FXMLLoader$ValueElement.processEndElement(FXMLLoader.java:801)
        at javafx.fxml/javafx.fxml.FXMLLoader.processEndElement(FXMLLoader.java:2969)
        at javafx.fxml/javafx.fxml.FXMLLoader.loadImpl(FXMLLoader.java:2654)
        ... 17 more
```

&lt;sup&gt;(i.e., it could not cast `List&lt;Node&gt;` to `Node`)&lt;/sup&gt;

---

# A Solution

If you want to keep the list of labels defined in your controller, then you can simply add those labels to the `VBox` in the `initialize` method.

```java
package list;

import java.util.List;
import javafx.fxml.FXML;
import javafx.scene.control.Label;
import javafx.scene.layout.VBox;

public class ListController {

    private final List&lt;Label&gt; list = List.of(new Label(&quot;Foo&quot;), new Label(&quot;Bar&quot;));

    @FXML
    private VBox box;

    @FXML
    private void initialize() {
        box.getChildren().addAll(list);
    }
}
```

This of course requires adding an appropriate `fx:id` attribute in the FXML file.

```xml
&lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot; encoding=&quot;UTF-8&quot;?&gt;

&lt;?import javafx.scene.layout.VBox?&gt;

&lt;VBox fx:id=&quot;box&quot; xmlns=&quot;http://javafx.com/javafx&quot; xmlns:fx=&quot;http://javafx.com/fxml&quot; 
      fx:controller=&quot;list.ListController&quot;&gt;
&lt;/VBox&gt;
```

Note that `List::of` returns an unmodifiable list. Modifying this list would not make much sense anyway, at least not after adding the elements to the `VBox`&#39;s children list, as modifying it would _not_ implicitly modify the children list. If labels can be added and removed, then you&#39;ll have to make sure the two lists are in sync (as well as use a modifiable list). In that case, it may make more sense to use an `ObservableList&lt;Label&gt;` and [bind the children list&#39;s content][2], assuming the `VBox` only contains those labels.

















  [1]: https://openjfx.io/javadoc/20/javafx.fxml/javafx/fxml/doc-files/introduction_to_fxml.html#read_only_list_property_elements
  [2]: https://openjfx.io/javadoc/20/javafx.base/javafx/beans/binding/Bindings.html#bindContent(java.util.List,javafx.collections.ObservableList)
  [3]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/util/List.html
  [4]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/util/ArrayList.html

